  qualityOfEarnings: "Earnings quality is the gating diligence item because Tamara is a balance-sheet lender, not a fee-only marketplace. What is stated and audited (via Argaam, FY25): net profit SAR 193.35m, net financing income SAR 763m (+144%), and the expected-credit-loss line falling to SAR 70.3m (9M-25) from SAR 176.4m (9M-24). What is inferred or undisclosed and must not be laundered as fact: GMV, Tamara's own blended take-rate (the ~4.25% widely cited is a Tabby+Tamara combined-model input, not company-reported), and — critically — loss rate as a % of the receivables book and the seasoning of the loss curve. A 60% drop in absolute ECL on a rapidly growing book can reflect genuine underwriting improvement OR book-mix/vintage timing where losses simply have not matured yet; the two are indistinguishable without cohort data. The profit also now depends on funding cost on the $2.4bn facility, so net financing income quality turns on the spread between yield and cost of funds, not take-rate alone. Late-fee elimination is a positive for revenue durability (no penalty-income reliance) but removes a historical revenue line, complicating YoY comparability. Diligence must require: (1) audited group financials and the full FY25 statements, not just the Argaam summary; (2) loss-by-cohort / vintage curves with 30/60/90-DPD buckets; (3) provisioning methodology and ECL staging under the SAMA regime; (4) the funding cost and covenant schedule on the $2.4bn facility; and (5) GMV and Tamara-specific take-rate disclosure under information rights.",
