  qualityOfEarnings:
    "Earnings quality cannot be assessed from public data — this is the central caveat of the deal. Lean has NEVER disclosed revenue, ARR, take-rate, gross margin, NRR or burn at any round, and no round valuation has ever been published. Every financial figure in this file is therefore estimated or illustrative, not stated: the ~$25m net-revenue anchor and the modelled revenue/EBITDA ramp are an analyst construct consistent with the stage, not company figures, and must not be read as disclosure. The hard, sourced facts are activity and funding metrics only: >$2bn A2A volume, ~1m connected accounts and >1bn transactions analysed are explicitly CUMULATIVE/lifetime — they size activity, not run-rate, and say nothing about how much of that volume converts to revenue. Even total raised (>$100m) is a floor, because the Mar-2025 Takamol Series B extension amount is undisclosed. The publicly cited proof points are CUSTOMER outcomes, not Lean economics: Tamara's reported '+32% approval-rate lift' and the '>$100m of card fees saved' for clients describe value delivered, and the card-fee-savings framing is in fact a flag that the realised A2A take-rate may be deliberately thin. Diligence must require, as gating conditions: audited financials (revenue, gross margin, EBITDA, burn/runway); the realised take-rate on A2A volume and its trend (revenue ÷ volume); ARR with a cohort/NRR analysis; revenue-by-client concentration (top-10); and the confirmed post-money on the round being priced. Until those are in hand, the franchise quality is plausible but the earnings are a black box — un-underwritable on price.",
