  "qualityOfEarnings": "Earnings quality cannot be assessed from outside — and that is the central diligence problem, not a footnote. Khazna is a G42 private subsidiary with no published P&L: revenue, EBITDA, utilisation, lease rates and contracted-backlog are all undisclosed. Everything financial in this memo is explicitly labelled: the ~$400m revenue base is ESTIMATED (~360MW operational × ~$1.5–2.0m/MW at partial fill), the ~45–52% EBITDA margin is a PEER BENCHMARK borrowed from Equinix/Digital Realty, and neither is a company figure — they are sizing aids that the first real data-room number would falsify. What is STATED and verifiable is physical: MW capacity, site count, the ~70%+ share, the $2.62bn facility, the Microsoft $5.2bn/200MW and Stargate commitments. The specific earnings-quality risks to underwrite: (1) revenue recognition and lease structure — are contracts take-or-pay with committed MW, or usage-based and therefore cyclical? (2) related-party pricing — what fraction of revenue is e&/G42/Core42 at arm's-length market rates vs intercompany? (3) capex-recovery curve and capitalised vs expensed cost — a capex-first build can flatter near-term EBITDA while depreciation and lease-up costs lag. Non-negotiable diligence requirements before any bid: audited financials (≥2 years), a tenant-by-tenant contracted-MW and WALT schedule with relatedness flagged, a utilisation/lease-up curve by site, the capex and drawn-leverage schedule against the ADCB+FAB covenants, and the basis for the 'presold >400MW' commentary (which is marketing, not an audited backlog). Until those exist, no figure here should be read as fact.",
  "recentDevelopments": "Company-specific (most recent first): (Dec-2025) Khazna entered Saudi Arabia, acquiring land for a first facility in Dammam of up to 200MW, and disclosed ~30 live facilities at 'almost 650MW' incl. construction. (Nov-2025) Microsoft and G42 agreed a ~$5.2bn / 200MW Azure expansion delivered through Khazna, online before end-2026, lifting Microsoft's UAE envelope to ~$15.2bn (2023–2029) — a hyperscaler-anchored demand print that materially de-risks near-term fill, with Microsoft securing US licences to export Nvidia A100/H100/GB300 chips after G42 gave security assurances. (Oct-2025) Khazna targeted full 1GW build-out of Stargate UAE (OpenAI/Oracle/Nvidia/Cisco/SoftBank) within three years, first 200MW live 2026. (Sep-2025) Closed the $2.62bn ADCB+FAB facility (≤10yr), among MENA's largest digital-infra financings. (Feb–Mar 2025) e& sold its 40% for $2.2bn (secondary → ~$5.5bn implied), with MGX and Silver Lake confirmed as minority holders alongside majority G42. Sector-level, synthesised: the UAE colocation market reached ~$1.74bn in 2026 (~17% CAGR to 2031) and the binding constraint across the industry has shifted from space to power, water and chips — operators (Khazna, DataVolt, Alfanar) are piloting liquid cooling to cut cooling-water use ~90%, and utilisation of powered shells now tracks Nvidia's supply roadmap and the US export regime rather than construction pace. Net: the demand and anchor-contract news since the $5.5bn mark has been strongly positive, but every catalyst (chips, power, licences) sits partly outside Khazna's control.",
