  "scenarioNarratives": {
    "bear": "No fresh raise materialises, or a primary round prices BELOW the (undisclosed) 2023 mark. Lean's first-mover SAMA licence and $67.5m war-chest let it win the enterprise PIS/payments contracts while Tarabut's licensure lags; coverage becomes stranded reach that never monetises. Cash deployed into Vyne thins runway, and Tarabut is acquired cheaply or recapitalised on dilutive terms. The coverage moat proves real but commercially inert — connectivity without a clearing take-rate. Capital is impaired. (No IRR asserted — there is no priced entry or disclosed financials to model a return from.)",
    "base": "Tarabut secures SAMA licensure on a lag behind Lean and holds a defensible share of a two-horse KSA market, converting part of its >60% coverage into paid PIS/A2A volume as the Vyne integration lands. Monetisation, once disclosed, clears at modest infra economics; the company raises a priced round at a flat-to-up mark and grows with the regulator-pulled market (MENA fintech ~12.5% CAGR). Outcome is a credible regional infra business heading toward a strategic sale — a sound venture-shaped result, but stage- and risk-profile-mismatched to this growth-equity mandate. (No IRR asserted — entry valuation is a placeholder, not a mark.)",
    "bull": "Tarabut obtains full SAMA licensure, the coverage advantage (>60% KSA, ~90% Bahrain, 17m+ accounts) converts into a leading paid-API + PIS/A2A take-rate, and Vyne makes it the payments-plus-data champion of the GCC rail. A scaled, profitable infra layer attracts a strategic acquirer — Visa (already an investor and owner of Tink) being the obvious buyer at a Tink-style multiple. This is the genuine upside, but it is contingent on three undisclosed unknowns turning favourable (licence, monetisation, cash) and on out-executing a freshly funded, already-licensed Lean. (No IRR asserted — no real valuation anchor exists; the magnitude is unquantifiable from public data.)"
  }
