  "qualityOfEarnings": "Earnings quality is unusually high for a venture-stage fintech but the disclosed surface is thin, so several load-bearing figures are inferred, not audited. STATED (company / PR Newswire, Nov-2025): >$1bn annualised revenue, FCF-positive as of Nov-1-2025, underlying profitability +153% YoY, 50,000+ customers, 2,200+ at $100k+ ARR (+133%), >$100bn annualised purchase volume; subsequently $1.5bn+ run-rate and 70,000+ customers at the Jun-2026 Series F. INFERRED: ~54% FY revenue growth is derived off the $648m FY2024 base (Sacra) — the company instead frames a $500m→$1bn '12-month doubling', so the growth rate the IC underwrites depends on which window is used; the two are not the same and should not be conflated. ESTIMATED / NOT DISCLOSED: the revenue-line split (~70% interchange / ~15% SaaS / bill pay / treasury) is third-party analyst estimate — Ramp does not disclose mix; gross margin is undisclosed (only inferred-positive from FCF status); net revenue retention, logo retention and churn — the single most important stickiness KPI for a multi-product attach thesis — are not disclosed. 'Annualised'/run-rate framing (×12 of a recent month) overstates vs trailing-twelve-month for a company growing this fast, so headline revenue should be read as run-rate, not booked TTM. Revenue recognition: interchange is recognised on transaction; SaaS over the subscription term; treasury 'yield' accrues via partner spread, not Ramp holding float — so it is not balance-sheet interest income and should not be modelled as such. DILIGENCE REQUIREMENTS before any commitment: (1) audited financials with the interchange/SaaS/bill-pay/treasury line split and gross margin; (2) NRR and logo-retention by cohort and by ARR band; (3) a TTM (not run-rate) revenue bridge; (4) interchange-rate and bank-partner-economics sensitivity; (5) FCF reconciliation (cash vs non-cash, SBC, working-capital float).",
  "recentDevelopments": "Company-specific (most recent first): (1) Jun-4-2026 — Ramp CLOSED a $750m Series F at a $44bn post-money (Iconiq, GIC and Ontario Teachers' leading; new investors Goldman Sachs Alternatives, D.E. Shaw, Morgan Stanley IM, Generation, Insight, BroadLight), with run-rate revenue cited at $1.5bn+, 70,000+ customers and FCF-positive; this is the LATEST mark and supersedes the May-2026 'in talks at >$40bn' reports — the IC underwrites the firm $32bn Nov-2025 Series E-3 entry, but should note the mark has since stepped up to $44bn (~29x the higher run-rate) and total capital raised now exceeds $3bn. CEO reiterated IPO interest with no timeline. (2) Nov-2025 — Series E-3, $300m at $32bn (Lightspeed-led, $90.00/share), the underwritten entry. (3) Aug-2025 — crossed $1bn annualised revenue. (4) Mar-2025 — secondary cleared at $13bn with ~$700m annualised revenue disclosed; the primary mark has therefore run $13bn→$32bn→$44bn in ~15 months. Sector-level: (a) Capital One acquired Brex for ~$5.15bn (closed Apr-7-2026), putting Ramp's nearest rival inside a bank — the defining competitive shift; (b) Navan IPO'd on Nasdaq (NAVN, Oct-2025), giving a public read on an interchange-heavy spend platform; (c) Paylocity folded Airbase into 'Paylocity for Finance', evidencing ERP/payroll bundling of spend management. Net: a strong operating tape, a still-richer mark, and a consolidating field — none of which resolves the entry-price or geography questions for this fund.",
